Lab 1.1: Installation and Basic Configuration
Step 1: Verify Running Instances
Execute this to check if both containers (default and named instance equivalents) are active.
docker ps


Expected Result: Table showing sql1 and sql2 containers with status Up.
Step 2: Connection Test (Default Instance)
Connect to the first instance and verify its name.
sqlcmd -S localhost,14331 -U sa -P 'YourStrongPassword123!' -C -Q "SELECT @@SERVERNAME"


Expected Result: Output showing the container ID or server name for the first instance.
Step 3: Check Server Properties
Retrieve version, edition, and collation information via CLI.
sqlcmd -S localhost,14331 -U sa -P 'YourStrongPassword123!' -C -Q "SELECT SERVERPROPERTY('ProductVersion') AS Version, SERVERPROPERTY('Edition') AS Edition, SERVERPROPERTY('Collation') AS Collation"


Expected Result: List showing version (e.g., 16.0.x), edition (Developer), and collation.
Step 4: Stop and Start Server
Demonstrate service management through Docker commands.
docker stop sql1
docker ps
docker start sql1
docker ps


Expected Result: sql1 disappears from the list after stop and reappears after start.
Step 5: Connection Test (Named Instance)
Connect to the second instance using its specific host port.
sqlcmd -S localhost,14332 -U sa -P 'YourStrongPassword123!' -C -Q "SELECT @@SERVERNAME"


Expected Result: Output showing the server name for the second instance.
Step 6: Verify Port Configuration
Confirm that the second instance is listening on the assigned external port.
docker inspect --format='{{range $p, $conf := .NetworkSettings.Ports}}{{$p}} -> {{(index $conf 0).HostPort}}{{end}}' sql2


Expected Result: 1433/tcp -> 14332.
